What you need to know:

In Europe and North America where cedar wood is exported to, it is used for the manufacture of pencils and penholders.The tree is often used in traditional African medicine. Scientific research has shown that the tree has active compounds that support the traditional uses.An infusion of the powdered young twigs is taken as a remedy against intestinal worms. The smoke from the twigs is inhaled as an expectorant.Cedar is easily propagated by seed which cost Sh2,000 per kilogramme at Kefri shops. The seeds store well and can be good for at least a year.